<TEXT>
President Reagan went horseback 
riding Sunday at his mountaintop ranch relaxing after a weekend 
summit in Mexico with President Miguel de la Madrid 
After breakfast with his wife Nancy Reagan saddled up for a 
ride along the trails of his 688acre spread in the Santa Ynez 
mountains Skies were clear and temperatures were warm in the 70s 
The Reagans who left Washington on Friday will remain at the 
ranch until Wednesday when they return to the White House on the 
eve of the unveiling of the budget proposal being sent to Congress 
for the fiscal year beginning Oct 1 
As Reagan relaxed White House chief of staff Howard Baker flew 
back to Washington leaving deputy chief of staff Kenneth 
Duberstein national security adviser Colin Powell and 
communications director Thomas Griscom as the senior officials with 
Reagan 
Powell and Griscom are to return to Washington on Tuesday a day 
ahead of the president The staff members stay at a Santa Barbara 
hotel about 25 miles from Reagans ranch 
Reagan arrived here Saturday evening after spending about four 
hours at a summit with de la Madrid at the Pacific coast resort of 
Mazatlan 
The annual meeting the sixth and final summit of the two 
outgoing presidents was marked by de la Madrids bluntly worded 
defense of Mexicos campaign to curb the production and trafficking 
of illegal drugs 
De la Madrid said Mexicos efforts were not appreciated and 
that the United States must do more to curb the demand for drugs 
which is at the source of the problem 
Reagan replied The people in the United States are now 
turning away from drugs a step he said should curb the demand 
that fuels the trafficking 
As Reagan flew to his ranch Saturday evening senior 
administration officials who accompanied him departed on their own 
flying back to Washington or other sites Secretary of State George 
P Shultz Attorney General Edwin Meese III Treasury Secretary 
James A Baker III and Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter had 
joined Reagan at the meeting 
